defaultIn Northern Ireland talk of a codified Constitution for the United Kingdom is likely to be divisive. Regardless of the content of any such codification, unionists will most probably see its very existence as a 
defaultc
defaultement
defaulting 
defaultof Northern Ireland’s current constitutional status, while nationalists will see it as an attempt to ignore th
defaulte fact that 
defaultNorthern Ireland is 
defaultmaterially 
defaultdifferent
default from other regions of the UK
default. During the recent debates on whether there should be a Bill
default of Rights for the United Kingdom
default (leading to the split report by the Commission 
defaulton a Bill of Rights 
defaultin December 2012)
default, many commentators of a nationalist disposition
default in Northern Ireland
default wanted nothing to do with the concept because they saw it as implying
default a strengthening of ties between Great Britain and Northern Ireland. Even if 
defaulta
default codified Constitution were to say nothing more about the constitutional status of Northern Ireland than what is already stated in the Northern Ireland Act 1998 (which reflects t
defaulthe Belfast (Good Friday) Agreement
default)
default, it would be portrayed by the various political parties in different ways. Unionists tend to see the Belfast (Good Friday) Agreement as conclusive
default – a 
defaultdestination. Nationalists tend to see it as transitional
default – a 
defaultstep
defaultping
default stone
default to something better (for them).
default&#xa0;
defaultIt follows that if the judiciary in Northern Ireland were to be involved in interpreting 
defaulta
default codified Constitution 
defaultthe judges would be
default 
defaultalmost 
defaultbound to 
defaultbe accused of being
default in some way politically biased.
default This criticism 
defaulthas not been made in recent years because
default, although
default the Northern Ireland Act 1998 is
default already
default a 
defaultkind of 
defaultconstitution for Northern Ireland, it is 
defaultnevertheless 
defaultan ordinary Act of Parliament
