defaultI am not sure that any formal consultation would be necessary, given the need to respect the separ
defaultation of powers doctrine. It would be unwise for judges to comment on potential provisions in a codified Constitution because they might then have to recuse themselves at a later stage if the meaning of the provisions were to come before them (see 
defaultDavidson
default v Scottish Ministers
default [2004] UKHL 34). The consultation that took place with the Law Lords when the establishment of the Supreme Court was proposed was more understandable, since the abolition of the Appellate Committee 
defaultwould have
default significant consequences for the judges’
default own
default 
defaulte
defaultnvironment
default and working methods
default; even so, the split which emerged amongst their Lordships 
defaulto
defaultn th
defaultat
default matter was embarrassing and 
defaultdid nothing to enhance p
defaultublic confidence in the independence of the judiciary.
default Askin
defaultg judges in Northern Ireland to comment on a draft codified Constitution would be most unwise as it would inevitably involve them in issues that are even more politically sensitive in Northern Ireland than in Great Britain.
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
defaultI believe it would be sensible to limit the courts’ power to issuing a ‘declaration of incompatibility with the Constitution’. As with
default declarations of incompatibility 
defaultthat can be 
defaultissued a
defaultlready
default under section 4 of the Human Rights Act 1998, such a declaration 
defaultw
defaultould not affect the validity of the piece of legislation in question nor alter the rights and duties of the parties to the litigation in which the matter arises. But there 
defaultw
defaultould 
defaultneed to 
defaultbe some provision in the Constitution which requires a parliamentary a
defaultnd/or governmental reaction to a judicial ‘declaration of incompatibility with the Constitution’
default – something a bit more mandatory than section 10 of the Human Rights Act 1998
default. Having a codified Constitution does not of itself require that a court be given 
defaultthe power to 
defaultinvalidate some law on the grounds of unconstitutionality. I think the model set by the Human Rights Act is ideal because it does not confer excessive power on judges, who 
defaulthave no electoral mandate
default, yet it imposes a
defaultn
default 
default(
defaultalbeit 
defaultweak)
default obligation o
defaultn the government to do something to correct the 
defaultincompatibility
default. 
defaultAfter the courts have issued a declaration of incompatibility with the Constitution o
defaultne option for the government would be to seek an amendment to the Constitution, through whatever mechanism
defaults are made available 
defaultfor that purpose
default in the Constitution itself, so as to make the challenged law 
defaultand the Constitution 
defaultno longer incompatible.
default 
default&#xa0;
defaultThe Committee might usefully examine the experience of the Republic of Ireland in this context. A commonly 
defaultheld view there is that on occasions the Supreme Court has wielded too much power by declaring certain legislative provisions to be unconstitutional. If the judges
default in Ireland
default had had a lesser power (e.g. to declare merely an incompatibility)
default,
default some undesira
