defaulta) What would be the implications of these powers on existing constitutional doctrines, including parliamentary sovereignty and judicial review?default&#xa0;
defaultAs stated above, it is possible to have a system whereby judges can declare Acts of Parliament to be incompatible with the Constitution but not invalidate them. But to maintain the credibility of the Constitution in such a situation it would be important t
defaulto have a provision in the Constitution mandating parliament and/or the government to react in a way which eliminates the incompatibility. It should be remembered that the Acts devolving power to the Scottish Parliament and to the Welsh and Northern Ireland
default Assemblies make provision for courts to suspend the effect of a declaration of legislative incompetence to allow time for the devolved government to rectify the matter
default. This was exercised for the first time in
default 
defaultSalvesen v Riddell
default [2013] UKSC 22.
default 
defaultb) In thdefaulte context of question 3, what can we learn from the interaction between the UK courts and the European Court of Justice and European Court of Human Rights?default&#xa0;
defaultI have made a detailed study of the interaction between the top UK court and the European Court of 
defaultHuman Rights (
defaultHuman Rights and the United Kingdom Supreme Court
default, OUP, 2013). I was able to demonstrate, I hope, that even today the top UK court and the Strasbourg Court are not always on the same wavelength – which is why a ‘dialogue’ between the courts i
defaults often useful. To date the Strasbourg Court has usually allowed member states a wide margin of appreciation as regards their internal constitutional arrangements (prisoner voting rights is an exception to this). Throughout the troubles in Northern Ireland
default the European Court of Human Rights did not play a significant role in protecting human rights in Northern Ireland: it really only began to do so after the ceasefires were announced in 1994. The Strasbourg Court continues to defer rather meekly to national
default governments when the latter decide that there is a public emergency threatening the life of the nation (see 
defaultA v UK
default (2009) 49 EHRR 29, the follow-up decision on the indefinite detention of foreign nationals in Belmarsh prison).
default&#xa0;
defaultThe nature of the jurisdict
defaultion of the Court of Justice of the EU (being mainly advisory, through ‘preliminary rulings’) is such that a codification of the UK’s Constitution ought not to make a significant difference. It is conceivable, though, that the 
defaultFactortame
default-type scenario – whe
defaultre a UK court is allowed to ‘disapply’ an Act of Parliament because of its inconsistency with EU law – could cause serious difficulties if it were 
defaultto arise in a context where the inconsistent provision was a provision in the Constitution. Given the anti-EU
default sentiments which seem to abound in certain political circles within the UK at the moment, it is entirely possible that the codified Constitution will contain such inconsistent provisions. The document will have to make it abundantly clear how any such inc
defaultonsistency is to be dealt with by the national judiciary. What the CJEU makes of the inconsistency is largely beyond the UK’s control. I do not think there is any particular Northern Irish dimension to this issue.  
default      
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
defaultA priori
default constitutional review is possible in Ireland and in France. On the 
defaultwhole, it has not worked particularly well
default in either jurisdiction
default. In Ireland the problem is that
default,
default once a court has made a decision on the constitutionality of a Bill before it becomes an Act
default,
default there can be no further challenge to the constitutionality of a
defaultny aspect of that Act after it has been passed (Article 
default34.3.3 of the 1937 Constitution). In France 
defaulta priori
default review by the Conseil constitutionnel was deemed to be an inadequate mechanism by itself, so in 2010 the Conseil was given the power to conduct 
defaulta 
defaultposteriori
default reviews as well. 
default&#xa0;
defaultIn general, judges rightly shy away from considering 
defaultt
defaulthe constitutionality of laws 
defaultin abstracto
default: they prefer to consider them in concrete cases. 
defaultIn Northern Ireland, since the Government of Ireland Act 1920, it has always been
default possible to refer Bills to a court 
defaultin order 
defaultto check whether the devolved legislature has the competence to make that law (the court in question used to be the Judicial Committee of the Privy Council but since 
defaultOctober 2009 it has been th
defaulte Supreme Court).
default 
defaultReferences to the Privy Council during the days of the Stormont Parliament were 
defaultvery 
defaultrare, and never led to a Bill being declared beyond th
defaultat
default Parliament’s competence. There has not yet been a reference to the Supreme Court
default concerning a Bill before the Nort
defaulthern Ireland Assembly
default.
default 
default&#xa0;
defaultPersonally I am in favour of 
defaulta priori
default consideration of Bills being left to the political domain. The availability of judicial review at the 
defaulta posteriori 
defaultstage should be an adequate safeguard. If the point is made that the latter depends on some wealthy and/or courageous litigant bringing the matter to court, this can be answered by giving a power to some external actor – the Attorney General or the Human R
defaultights Commission perhaps – to bring the matter to court, much as the Northern Ireland Human Rights Commission 
defaulthas done
default in relation to the inability of unmarried couples to apply to adopt children
default (
defaultRe NIHRC’s Application for Judicial Review
default [2013] NICA 37)
default.
