default&#xa0;
defaultIn 
default2004 I published a chapter in an edited collection in which I considered, but rejected, the idea that 
defaultthere should be a Constitutional Court for Northern Ireland (‘A Constitutional Court f
defaulto
defaultr Northern Ireland?’ in Andrew Le Sueur
default (ed)
default, 
defaultBuilding the UK’s New Supreme Court
default, OUP, 2004, 49-66
default).
default I hold the same view in relation to the idea of a Constitutional Co
defaulturt for the United Kingdom. I support the view that the Supreme Court should be the final court for all legal matters in the United Kingdom, constitutional or otherwise. The fact that the Supreme Court is currently, in effect, the constitutional court as f
defaultar 
defaultas 
defaultthe extent of dev
defaulto
defaultl
defaultv
defaulted
default powers are concerned is evidence of the fact that that court can consider constitutional issues just as effectively as any other body. Besides, the demarcation of labour issues that can arise whenever a country has more than on
defaulte top court make it sensible to 
defaulthave
default a more hierarchical structure. South Africa, France and Germany all suffer from 
defaultdemarcation issues
default to some extent, although Germany less so on account of its clearer provisions on jurisdiction.
default&#xa0;
defaultIf a separate Constituti
defaultonal Court were to be created, the system for appointing its members would need to ensure that a view from Northern Ireland (and other devolve regions) is available to the Court.    
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
defaultI addressed this precise issue during the course of my inaugural professorial lecture at 
defaultQueen’s University in 2006 (
default‘
defaultThe role of judges in the development of constitutions’ (2006) 57 Northern Ireland Legal Quarterly 332-351
default; appended to this evidence
default). At pages 337 to 344 I drew upon the experience of the US, France, Ireland, India, South Afr
defaultica and Canada to show what judges 
defaultcan 
defaultdo to support constitutionalism. I then made ten suggestions for how judges should reform the UK’s Constitution (pages 344 to 
default351). 
default&#xa0;
defaultIt must be remembered that the power of judges in the US to strike down Acts of Con
defaultgress as unconstitutional was not conferred by the US Constitution but was grabbed by the Supreme Court in 
defaultMarbury v Madison 
default(1803). What makes the power of the US Supreme Court somewhat frightening in this context – and the underlying reason, perhaps, why
default the Court has been much criticised of late for being too activist – is the fact that amending the US Constitution is very difficult indeed to achieve, as the 
defaultfailure to obtain enough state ratifications for the Equal Rights Amendment in 1982 (guaranteeing
default rights for women) clearly indicates. 
default&#xa0;
defaultOn the other hand, it is commonly acknowledged that the Supreme Court of India has been 
defaulttoo
default activist in recent years, usurping the powers of the Indian Parliament and in effect making laws that the judges have no rea
defaultl expertise in devising. Australia, to my mind, is a good example of where the written Constitution of 1900 has had a deleterious effect on the judiciary: it has forced them to spend a lot of time trying to interpret language that is out of date and not ob
defaultviously relevant to the 21st century. Some would say the same about the US Constitution, as evidenced by the US Supreme Court’s recent decision on the right to bear arms: 
defaultDistrict of Columbia v Heller
default 554 US 570 (2008). 
default&#xa0;
defaultIf we are not to lead ou
defaultr
default judges down blind alleys and on wild goose chases we must ensure that any codified Constitution clearly sets out not just the powers of the judges but also the limits to those powers and the ways in which the
default judges
default should go about exercising them.    
