defaultAPPENDIXdefaultTHE ROLE OF JUDGES defaultIN THE DEVELOPMENT OF CONSTITUTIONSdefault&#xa0;
defaultIntroductiondefaultThe debate about the role of judges in the British constitution has been prolific and fierce in recent years. It has, though, tended to focus too much on history and not enough on possible futures. It has concentrated on the ‘is’ and 
defaultnot on the ‘ought’. And, like many debates, it has degenerated into one where there are basically two opposing camps, neither of which is prepared to give much ground to the other. There are a few outliers, but these too tend to squabble over their exact p
defaultosition vis-à-vis the other protagonists rather than rising above the fray and adopting a more positive frame of mind. What is needed is a more holistic approach, one which recognises that there are advantages in both main positions, as well as in their va
defaultriants, but which prefers to focus not on whether judges are more important than law-making politicians in maintaining constitutionalism but on what steps each of those élites should take to copper-fasten the constitution against the vicissitudes of 21
defaultst
default c
defaultentury living. Judges in most other countries do play a crucial role in developing their national constitutions. Judges in the UK have, on the whole, underperformed in that area, at least in the last few decades. Now is the time for them to raise their gam
defaulte. 
defaultThe article begins by summarising the current debate. It then proceeds to review some of the contributions made by judges to constitutions elsewhere than in the United Kingdom. In its final section it makes and tries to justify ten suggestions as to ho
defaultw Britain’s top judges should reform the British constitution. Throughout, the article takes a broad approach to the term ‘constitution’. In particular it embraces within that term the rules and principles governing judicial freedom of action.    
defaultThe currdefaultent debatedefaultIn March 2004 Adam Tomkins delivered his inaugural lecture as the Professor of Public Law at the University of Glasgow, a lecture which he later expanded into book form.
default In this book he launched a passionate attack against those who advocate th
defaulte theory known as ‘common law constitutionalism’ – the idea that at the core of the British constitutional order lies the common law made by judges. Tomkins belittled the views of commentators such as Jeffrey Jowell and Dawn Oliver at University College Lo
defaultndon and Paul Craig at Oxford. He had the temerity to undermine that guru of the common law, Ronald Dworkin.
default And he had a go, too, at Sir John Laws, the Court of Appeal judge who has extolled the virtues of the common law in extra-judicial writings
default as we
defaultll as in his own judgments.
default Particular opprobrium, however, 
defaultwas reserved for Trevor Allan at Cambridge.
default Tomkins described Allan as a ‘hardliner’ and labelled the breadth of his support for constitutional justice as ‘staggering’. To Allan, said Tomkins, ‘it seems that there is no constitutional problem that is incapable of being solved by the courts and [tha
defaultt] no constitutional problem is solved until it is solved by the courts’. Tomkins thought this was ‘legal constitutionalism at its most extreme’.
default 
defaultInstead of relying upon the courts as the guardians of the constitution, Tomkins promotes the notion of 
default‘political accountability’. Prior to acquiring his chair he had written articles defending what he called ‘the political constitution’,
default a throwback to the phrase used by John Griffith in the 1970s.
default In such works Tomkins has to some extent been following 
defaultthe lead given by Martin Loughlin at the London School of Economics and Political Science, in three books published since 1992.
default The reliance placed by Tomkins and Loughlin on the essentially political nature of the constitution  is not so very far removed
default from the views of those who, like Christopher Forsyth and Mark Elliott at Cambridge,
default still maintain the rather Diceyean line that all judicial development of the law must ultimately be traced back to the supposed intention of Parliament. Tomkins’ approac
defaulth has to some extent been bolstered by the likes of Thomas Poole, who claims that common law constitutionalism fails to adequately explain the main features of the way judicial review actually operates in Britain.
default Poole sees judges as aristocrats and mora
defaultl imperialists.
default Another lawyer at Glasgow, Gavin Anderson, makes three further criticisms of common law constitutionalism (or, rather, of what he calls ‘rights constitutionalism’): he believes that it fails to control private, as opposed to public, power;
default it 
defaultignores the significance of the practices and actors of the global economy; and it considerably overstates the capacity of judges to be coherently instrumental.
default In Anderson’s words, ‘judges, like other law-creating subjects, construct distinctive pers
defaultonal accounts of the legal world, whose mutual interaction necessarily leads to inconsistency and contradiction’.
default 
defaultNot surprisingly, well-known attempts have been made to pigeon-hole those who write in this area by giving them fancy labels. Martin Loughli
defaultn describes people who place great emphasis on the work of the courts as ‘conservative normativists’; those who prefer to place their trust in Parliament and in politics, Loughlin calls ‘functionalists’.
default He reserves a third label for people who believe th
defaultat courts should not have the final say over everything but should at least articulate principles which can guide the executive in the exercise of its discretions. This category should, I think, embrace people like Sir William Wade (that much-lamented icon
default of British constitutional law who died in 2005
default), Robert Stevens (still writing about British judges 50 years after his first article was published
default) and Sir Neil MacCormick, the eminent legal philosopher at Edinburgh whose latest book, 
defaultRhetoric and the R
defaultule of Law
default, provides many insights into the nature of judicial reasoning. These people, in Loughlin’s terms, are ‘liberal normativists’. If, like me, you have an in-built aversion to such grandiose labels you might prefer the much more prosaic categories s
defaultuggested by Carol Harlow and Richard Rawlings, who simply talk of red-light and green-light approaches.
defaultMy own approach lies somewhere between red and amber. In Loughlin’s terms I’d be a ‘liberal-conservative normativist’. This means that, in my view, jud
defaultges can and should play a very significant role in shaping constitutions. They should actively seek to control both the government and Parliament, preventing those institutions from damaging the rule of law and the separation of powers. There should be ver
defaulty few issues which are non-justiciable. At the same time, the power of judges should not be unbridled. The judiciary should be just one site in which sovereignty is located. Power must also reside in other sites,
default and values other than legal ones must be p
defaultromoted. But judges bring relative detachment, valuable experience and absolute integrity to their work. We should, therefore, give them a fairly free rein.
default We should not, I think, adopt the approach of Horace Walpole, who in 1770 wrote in a letter: ‘Ever
defaultybody talks of the constitution, but all sides forget that the constitution actually works 
defaultextremely well, if they would let it alone’.
default Letting it alone should not be considered an option today.
default 
defaultIn any event, the critics of common law constitutionalism 
defaulttend to ignore some important ‘modern’ features of the British legal system. For a start, they do not generally respect the influence of European institutions. Anyone wishing to remind themselves of that influence should consult the writings of Nicholas Ba
defaultmforth.
default He brings a dose of realism to the debate by observing that no theory about today’s UK constitution can be valid unless it explains why a British court will ‘disapply’ an Act of Parliament if it is inconsistent with EC law or why, as a result of t
defaulthe Human Rights Act, courts are free to disagree with Parliament – not just with government – that a piece of primary legislation is compatible with the European Convention on Human Rights. Bamforth endorses what Gordon Anthony usefully describes as the ‘s
defaultpill-over’ effect – the idea that courts in the UK are influenced by European considerations even though the specific matter at issue is not regulated by EC law or the Convention.
default The main message coming from Bamforth’s and Anthony’s analyses, with which 
defaultI agree, is that reports of the death of common law constitutionalism are greatly exaggerated. 
defaultAnd if such reports were exaggerated three or four years ago, they are even more so today because in the last few years there has been a renaissance of interest
default in the rule of law on the part of our top judges, the Law Lords. Those judges are, of course, about to metamorphose into Justices of the UK’s Supreme Court,
default although not, it seems, before October 2009.
default When that occurs, their role as guardians of our co
defaultnstitution will surely become even more obvious.
default As it is, Law Lords are already standing their ground against New Labour’s increasing authoritarianism.
default Their two recent decisions on the position of foreign detainees at Belmarsh prison are, it is to be h
defaultoped, not just straws in the wind but emblems of a whole new spirit of judicial activism.
default At the end of 2004 eight Law Lords ruled that internment 
defaultwithout trial under the Anti-terrorism, Crime and Security Act 2001 was contrary to the European Convention’
defaults guarantee of the right not to be deprived of liberty on a discriminatory or disproportionate basis.
default They measured the Act against Article 15 of the Convention, which is not one of the articles incorporated by the Human Rights Act, so this is a further e
defaultxample of Anthony’s ‘spill-over’ effect. A year later a unanimous bench of seven Law Lords ruled that no British court can rely upon evidence that may have been obtained anywhere in the world through the use of torture.
default 
default&#xa0;
defaultA close reading of the judgments 
defaultin both those cases could surely leave no-one in any doubt that the highest court in the land plays an absolutely crucial role not just in protecting human rights but in curbing the excesses of Parliament and the executive. Yet in his comments on the first
default of these decisions, Adam Tomkins damns with faint praise.
default He claims that the Law Lords were ‘merely following a path already broken by others’ and that ‘the change of tone…should not mislead us into thinking that it heralds a change of approach’. His jus
defaulttification for this view is that after the judgments were issued the Belmarsh detainees were still in prison and the rest of the Anti-terrorism Act was still on the statute book. He seems to be saying that unless judges can completely usurp the functions o
defaultf elected politicians they are entirely useless. To adapt his own phrase, this is surely republicanism at its most extreme. 
defaultTo appreciate better the contribution judges could and should make to the UK’s constitution one needs to look abroad.
default The next sec
defaulttion of this article will conduct a brief survey of some leading liberal democracies to see what innovations could possible be mirrored in Britain. 
defaultContributions to constitutionalism made by judges elsewheredefault 
defaultThe American Constitution, one often reads, is
default be applauded for the way it permits the Supreme Court to invalidate Acts of Congress if they are ‘unconstitutional’. But of course that power was not conferred by the 1787 document signed by George Washington and others, nor by the first 10 amendments whi
defaultch were agreed in 1791 and which we call the Bill of Rights. Instead, the power was created 
defaultfor itself
default by the US Supreme Court. In 
defaultMarbury v Madison
default,
default 
defaultin 1803, Chief Justice Marshall skilfully gave President Jefferson the result he was 
defaulthoping for by holdin
defaultg that the attempt by the previous President, John Adams, to appoint a number of federal judges before he left office, was ineffective. This was because the Act of Congress
default authorising the Court to enforce the appointments was held not to be valid. Under 
defaultArticle III of the Constitution the Court had been given a number of specific functions and without express authorisation Congress had tried to expand those functions. Very cleverly the Court denied to itself the lesser power to enforce judicial appointmen
defaultts but in the very act of doing so conferred on itself the much greater power to declare Acts of Congress to be unconstitutional.
defaultIt is on this slender foundation the whole edifice of judicial review in America has subsequently been constructed, although i
defaultnstances of Acts being declared unconstitutional remain rare. It did occur when Franklin Roosevelt was pursuing his New Deal ideology in the 1930s, and the Supreme Court’s stance on that occasion is sometimes taken, wrongly I think, as an illustration of j
defaultudicial opposition in America to the notion of social and economic rights.
default The truth is that the New Deal case turned on a different point altogether, namely on whether Congress had delegated too much power to an administrative agency without giving it ad
defaultequate guidance on how to exercise that power. If anything, therefore, the decision was a blow in favour of constitutionalism and a few years later the Supreme Court had little difficulty in upholding different New Deal legislation which was more clearly d
defaultrafted.
defaultBut it is worth noting that in recent years considerable scepticism has been voiced in America about the current Supreme Court’s commitment to constitutionalism. Disdain for judges’ constitutional work has been displayed, for example, by Mark Tush
defaultnet of Georgetown Law School, in books with provocative titles such as 
defaultThe New Constitutional Order 
defaultand 
defaultTaking the Constitution Away from the Courts
default, where he argues that the credit usually accorded to the US Supreme Court for maintaining the rule of law 
defaultis grossly overestimated. Others have taken up the same theme. Robert Bork, whose nomination to the Supreme Court by President Reagan was vetoed by the Senate in 1987, recently published a book condemning what he calls ‘the world-wide rule of judges’.
default Mar
defaultk Levin, likewise, has written a study entitled 
defaultMen in Black: How the Supreme Court is Destroying America
default. And Jeremy Waldron, a New Zealander now based in New York, maintains the same line.
default Some legal academics are less sweeping in their condemnation, bu
defaultt in the lead-up to the not unexpected death of Chief Justice Rehnquist in 2005, and in the commentaries on the appointment of John Roberts as his successor, there have been numerous negative assessments of how little the US Supreme Court has contributed t
defaulto constitutionalism in recent times.
default Its somewhat half-hearted efforts to control the American government’s excesses during the current ‘war on terror’ are, to many, 
defaultsymptomatic of the malaise.
default If the UK’s judges are failing to rise to constitutional cha
defaultllenges, it seems that American judges, despite having a much greater tradition in the field, and more ‘weapons’ at their disposal, are also in need of strong encouragement to be more active.           
defaultIn America the review of the constitutionality of pri
defaultmary legislation can occur only 
defaultafter
default it has been enacted. In France it can occur only 
defaultbeforehand
default. The Constitution of the Fifth Republic, in place since 1958, created a body known as the Constitutional Council (
defaultLe Conseil constitutionnel
default).
default This body is n
defaultot actually a court at all and its nine members are not judges, but one of its functions is to examine draft statutes (
defaultlois
default) to see if they conform with the Constitution. The Councillors do not read or listen to arguments put by advocates for the opposing 
defaultpoints of view. They do their own thinking, taking account only of documents preceding the draft law and of the French Constitution itself. But they have been adept at reading into that Constitution additional criteria for assessing whether laws are in con
defaultformity with it. 
defaultThe turning point came in 1971. A year earlier the French Cabinet had ordered the dissolution of a small left-wing political party, 
defaultLa Gauche Prolétarienne
default. In response to this, activists such as Jean-Paul Sartre and Simone de Beauvoir se
defaultt up another group named after the newspaper of the banned party, 
defaultLa Cause du Peuple
default. The government directed the local prefect not to register this new group but a local administrative court rather bravely ruled that the prefect had no such power to refus
defaulte registration. The government then introduced a Bill to widen the prefect’s powers and it was this Bill which the Constitutional Council struck down. It did so by implying into the Constitution the so-called ‘fundamental principles recognised by the laws 
defaultof the Republic’, a phrase mentioned in the Preamble to the 1946 Constitution of the Fourth French Republic and deemed to be affirmed by the Preamble to the 1958 Constitution.
default One of these principles, said the Council, was that of freedom of association. 
defaultAnd it is on the back of that momentous decision that the Constitutional Council has since built an envious reputation for guaranteeing civil liberties in France. Last year the Council pronounced on 18 draft laws. This year it has already invalidated parts
default of the proposed anti-terrorism law,
default although it upheld the controversial youth employment law, which was found not to be in breach of the principle of equality.
default Of course, political and popular pressure later conspired to force President Chirac to suspe
defaultnd that law, a move which prompted a recent commentator to suggest that the ritual of mass protests reversing 
defaultunpopular governmental measures should actually be regarded as an informal part of the French constitution.
default 
defaultThe French Council has another impor
defaulttant function – the supervision of elections. That responsibility also fell to the US Supreme Court when Al Gore challenged the electoral victory of George W Bush in 2000. The Court split 5 to 4 in favour of not permitting any further recounting of the vot
defaultes in Florida, thereby handing the presidency to Mr Bush.
default Analysts usually observe that there was an uncanny alignment between the supposed political views of the nine US justices and the ultimate outcome of the case, but whether any of the judges actuall
defaulty allowed their personal political predilections to influence their voting is impossible to verify. Their political predilections could have been the 
defaultresult
default of, rather than the 
defaultcause
default of, their conception of the role of judges in developing the constitution
default. Adam Tomkins would probably condemn this case as another lamentable example of unhelpful judicial interference in constitutional affairs, but if so he would also have to condemn the involvement of the highest civil court in Italy
default when, earlier this year
default, it confirmed the electoral victory of Romano Prodi. As we know from the experience of Germany last year and Iraq this year, courts may not be able to force politicians into coalitions, but they can at least determine who won most votes at an election. If
default a top court is not the right body to decide that, who is?  And, by the way, according to opinion polls, the reputation of the American Supreme Court hardly suffered at all as a result of its intervention in 
defaultBush v Gore
default.
defaultThe American Court has also been a
defaultctive in developing ‘unenumerated’ constitutional rights – rights which are not expressly mentioned in the Constitution, but which judges see as implicit. But we do not need to cross the Atlantic, or even the English Channel, to encounter judges who are pr
defaultepared to invent such rights. Just down the road is a jurisdiction where the Supreme Court has been remarkably active in doing just that.  Ireland even allows its judges to assess the constitutionality of legislation 
defaulteither before or after
default its enactment.
default 
defaultOne of the unenumerated rights in Ireland is the right to privacy. The others include the right to strike, the right to earn a living, the right to communicate, the right to access the courts, the right to 
defaultbe legally represented if facing criminal charges,
default the right to protection of one’s health, the right to travel, the right to found a family and the right to know the identity of one’s natural mother. All of these rights are creations of the common law.
default Not everyone is a fan of how the Irish judges have 
defaultgone about their task – David Gwynn Morgan at Cork (I think he goes with full title, i.e. David Gwynn Morgan), for example, is critical of their inconsistency and of their reliance on principles which to him are not rational.
default Furthermore, in the last few 
defaultyears a marked conservatism has become evident within the Irish Supreme Court.
default Worrying examples are the case of Jamie Sinnott, a young autistic man who was, in effect, denied the right to education,
default and the case of 
defaultTD
default,
default where only one judge, Mrs Justice
default Denham, was bold enough to order the government to provide support units for teenagers with behavioural difficulties – the other judges saw that as a step too far for the judiciary, a step that would breach the doctrine of separation of powers by allowing
default judges to do what was supposedly the preserve of Dáil Éireann.  
defaultIn this respect the Irish Supreme Court has not followed the lead of the Supreme Court of India, which has come under attack not for being judicially 
defaultinactive
default but for being judicially 
defaultover-a
defaultctive
default. It has been particularly imaginative in developing the right to life and personal liberty, which is guaranteed by Article 21 of the Indian Constitution of 1950 but which, thanks to the Supreme Court, now embraces as well the right to shelter, the ri
defaultght to health, the right to work, the right to clean air and clean water and the right to information. In a recent case brought by a journalist, the Indian Supreme Court relied on the right to equality in Article 14 of the Constitution to order criminal ju
defaultstice agencies to investigate the alleged financing of terrorist organisations by high-ranking politicians.
default This prompted one critic to remark that what was formerly judicial activism had evolved into judicial arrogance
default and he warned that unless the Supr
defaulteme Court exercises restraint, ‘the activist profile may be the first footprints of an impending constitutional lawlessness in India’.
default       
defaultWell, maybe the Indian court 
defaulthas
default gone too far, and maybe the Irish court 
defaultis
default wise to be cautious. But in the UK ju
defaultdges are a long way from reaching those outer limits of constitutional activism. And they have far to go before coming anywhere near the role played by the Constitutional Court of South Africa or, in recent years, by the Supreme Court of Canada, although t
defaulthose courts do benefit from having very modern constitutional documents from which to work. It was apparent from its earliest judgments in the mid-1990s
default that the 
defaultSouth African Court was going to be one which grounded its decisions in a purposive interpret
defaultation of the country’s Constitution, which came to its conclusions only after considering how courts in other parts of the world – and not just courts based on the Anglo-Saxon model – had resolved similar issues, and which contained judges who couched thei
defaultr judgments not in vapid legal jargon but in inspirational phrases.
default The Court has also been refreshingly pragmatic, best illustrated perhaps in its use of the power to suspend the invalidation of legislation until the government has had a reasonable time 
defaultto amend it.
default This is a power which the Federal Constitutional Court of Germany has also conferred upon itself.
default And the South African Court has pronounced at length on the scope of social and economic rights, yet without usurping the mandate of elected po
defaultliticians in that domain.
default 
defaultCanada, too, has benefited from having a Supreme Court that is imaginative and internationalist in its outlook, although in the view of one commentator, there is ‘no set of judges in the developed world who are treated by the 
defaultgeneral population with such glowering suspicion’.
default My colleague Rory O’Connell has made a special study of the ‘political’ role of the court
default and is currently analysing how it has innovatively developed the concept of equality. The leading Canadian schola
defaultr in this field, Kent Roach, has shown in his book 
defaultThe Supreme Court on Trial
default, that ‘an independent and courageous judiciary is the best institution we have to remind us of’ the effects of our actions on the unpopular and the disadvantaged.
default One of the num
defaulterous decisions Roach highlights
default is that here the Supreme Court read into the human rights code of Alberta the right not be discriminated against on the basis of sexual orientation, even though the legislature had deliberately omitted that right.
default  
defaultSo, a
defaultll over the world top courts have deployed considerable imagination in developing their national constitutions. And frequently they have achieved this without relying upon the specific wording of their constitution. New Zealand, like Britain, does not have
default a written constitution, but that has not stopped the highest court there from ruling that people should be compensated if their fundamental human rights are breached.
default It is worth remembering, too, that 
defaultinternational
default courts play an ever more important rol
defaulte in promoting constitutionalism. Some would say that the European Court of Justice, like the Indian Supreme Court, has been a little 
defaulttoo
default enthusiastic in doing just that.
default Steven Greer, at Bristol, argues that the European Court of Human Rights has devised
default both primary and secondary constitutional principles to guide its own adjudication processes.
default Certainly that Court has judged important constitutional issues arising within Britain. It has ruled that it is not contrary to basic democratic principles to a
defaultllow members of Parliament to be immune from being sued for whatever they say in Parliament.
default It has also insisted, in a case that came from Guernsey, that judicial power must be wielded completely separately from executive or legislative power,
default a decisio
defaultn which prompted the British Lord Chancellor to announce that he would no longer sit as a judge. And in what seems to me a less impressive decision, the European Court upheld the quaint rule that no-one can sit in the British Parliament unless he or she is
default prepared to swear 
defaultpersonal
default allegiance to the Queen.
default That, surely, must be an aberration? 
defaultSuggestions for how judges should reform the UK constitutiondefault&#xa0;
defaultSo courts elsewhere have managed to develop constitutions quite significantly. This final section of t
defaulthe article makes a number of suggestions as to how UK judges should amend the British constitution – without the need for Parliamentary or governmental approval. These changes would create a more ‘constitutionalised’ state, meaning that the distribution an
defaultd 
defaultexercise of power would be controlled in a more consistent and principled fashion and that people would be left with a greater sense of being citizens of the world rather than of one small corner of it, Within the last century British judges have been un
defaultnecessarily timid in the constitutional field.
default The time has come for them to be more assertive.
default 
defaultFirst, British judges should resurrect and develop the concept of ‘constitutional rights’. A few judges did flirt with this idea in pre-Human Rights Act days
default, in cases like 
defaultLeech
default, 
defaultWitham
default and 
defaultSimms
default.
default Now that that Act has embedded most of the Convention rights in our domestic law the time seems to me to be riper than ever for the enunciation of rights unenumerated in that Act. Such a position is supported by at
default least two former Law Lords,
default and also by the Cambridge scholar Mark Elliott.
default Unfortunately, as I tried to indicate in the memorial lecture for Stephen Livingstone earlier this year,
default Britain’s Law Lords have been unwilling to go beyond Convention rights 
defaultby affirming the existence of additional rights under the common law. In particular they failed to do so in the Northern Irish case of 
defaultCullen
default,
default where a person held in custody was, in defiance of the rules, denied access to a solicitor at certain times. By 
default3 to 2 (with Lords Bingham and Steyn dissenting) the Lords refused to award any compensation for this breach of rights. Very regrettably, just a month ago the House set its face more firmly than ever against the idea of developing the concept of constituti
defaultonal rights: in 
defaultWatkins v Home Office
default 
defaultthey held that if prison officers maliciously interfere with a prisoner’s correspondence with his solicitor, they will not be liable to pay compensation if no actual loss has been suffered by the prisoner. Lord Bingha
defaultm seemed to go back on what he 
defaultsaid in 
defaultCullen
default and joined Lord Rodger in claiming that the fact that the Human Rights Act was now in force was a further reason for 
defaultnot
default developing the concept of constitutional rights. With respect, I think that is misguided.
default There is surely much more to rights under the constitution than the concept of human rights? In my view the three key constitutional rights which judges should immediately develop and provide compensation for if breached are the right to access to justic
defaulte,
default the right to equality
default and the right to fairness in decision-making.
default     
defaultMy second suggested reform is that judges should develop the idea of positive state duties as the corollary of constitutional rights. They should steal a march on their Strasbou
defaultrg colleagues in this regard, for the latter have been a bit hesitant in fashioning duties out of Articles in the European Convention.
default To some extent British judges have already developed positive duties based on Article 2,
default but there is a lot more they c
defaultould do vis-à-vis, say, Articles 3 and 8. For instance, if women have the right not to be subjected to domestic violence, should the state not be under a duty to provide refuges and other support facilities for abused women? And if we all have the right to
default be free from degrading treatment and personally secure, should judges not oblige the state to protect us against environmental degradation? The Indian Supreme Court has been severely criticised for inappropriate meddling in environmental issues,
default but in B
defaultritain the courts have been almost completely silent in the area. 
default Thirdly, judges should assert more forcefully their power to review the exercise of Crown prerogatives. There is no need to follow Tomkins in calling for a Prerogative (Abolition) Act.
default Th
defaulte decision in the 
defaultGCHQ
default case, back in 1984,
default was clearly a missed opportunity to subject the government more meaningfully to the rule of law. Although the European Court of Human Rights agreed that considerations of national security justified the British g
defaultovernment’s ban on trade unions at the site in question,
default the House of Lords could surely have been more interventionist in assessing the strength of the government’s claim. True, 
defaultlater cases have shown that the courts are sometimes willing to intervene on other prerogative powers, such as the power to issue pas
defaultsports,
default to grant pardons
default or to to render diplomatic assistance to a British subject who is suffering violation of a fundamental human right as the result of the conduct of the authorities of a foreign state.
default Given recent controversies over peerages for 
defaultdonors of money, maybe judges will soon get the opportunity to decide whether certain honours have been legally bestowed. And it is not inconceivable that the lawfulness of resort to foreign military action will soon or later be justiciable, whether or not
default Parliamentary approval is also required.
default  But Britain still awaits its equivalent to the Watergate case in America.
default There the Supreme Court recognised that the President does have the right to keep many conversations confidential, but it nevertheless he
defaultld that the duty to ensure fairness in a criminal trial overrides that privilege. Richard Nixon resigned as President two weeks after the Supreme Court’s decision.
default The closest Britain has come to this degree of scrutiny of executive privilege was probably
default during the recent Hutton Inquiry into the death of David Kelly.
default The outcome of that inquiry is for present purposes irrelevant, but what 
defaultis
default worth noting is the irony that a Law Lord who was not presiding in a court and who could not make any judgment as 
defaultto civil or criminal liability was nevertheless supplied with more information than he would have been given if he had been so presiding – he even got to see Alastair Campbell’s private diary! 
defaultMy fourth suggestion is that the doctrine which allows foreign
default governments to claim sovereign immunity when sued in the United Kingdom needs to be restricted. The primacy of customary international law should be recognised. For example, people who are the victims of state-sponsored torture abroad should be able to su
defaulte the foreign governments in British courts
default and, if they win, they should be able to enforce the judgment against the foreign government’s assets in this country. As it happens, an appeal dealing with this point has just concluded in the House of Lords.
default 
defaultWhen they are writing their judgments let’s hope the Law Lords in that case make as good a use of international law as they did in the two Belmarsh cases
default and in the Pinochet case some years ago.
default  
defaultFifthly, as I argued in the Livingstone lecture,
default judges 
defaultshould put a severe dent in the constitutional principle that international treaties ratified by the government have no effect 
defaultwithin our national legal system unless they have been expressly incorporated into our law.
default In the Northern Irish case of 
defaultMcKerr
default case, two years ago,
default Lord Steyn called for this dualist approach to international law to be reconsidered. A majority of judges in the High Court of Australia came to the same conclusion nearly 10 years before that,
default though it is fair to say that the idea
default has not since taken root there and, apart from its work on the rights of indigenous peoples,
default the Australian Court has a record that is probably worse than that of the House of Lords in implying constitutional rights.
default Of course allowing treaties to have 
defaultan 
defaulteffect 
defaultdoes not mean that they have to become 
defaultbinding
default: judges should develop a rebuttable presumption that national law 
defaultmust 
defaultbe read in a way which makes it consistent with ratified treaties unless there are very strong policy reasons why an inconsisten
defaultcy should be preserved. This would go further than the principle of statutory construction which is currently applied, namely, that statutes are to be read as consistent with ratified treaties only if they are reasonably capable of bearing such a meaning.
defaultSixthly, judges should expand still further the sources they are prepared to look at before they decide cases. At present they very largely restrict themselves to ‘legal’ sources, ignoring information which is primarily economic or sociological in nature.
default They should, in short, accept American-style ‘Brandeis briefs’.
default Provided limits are placed on the size of such documents, and that resort to oral argument is more time-limited, as it is in the Washington and Strasbourg courts, there is no reason to belie
defaultve that proceedings in British courts would be unduly lengthened as a result of this reform.   
defaultSeventhly, and this links to the point just made, judges need to commit themselves to a much more contextual approach to statutory interpretation, one that goes
default beyond the requirement in section 3 of the Human Rights Act 1998 that legislation must be read and given effect in a way which is compatible with Convention rights ‘so far as it is possible to do so’.
default An archetypal example of this 
defaultnot
default happening is the re
defaultcent case of 
defaultR v J
default,
default where a man in his thirties who had allegedly had repeated sex with a 13-year-old girl was charged with indecent assault on a woman, contrary to section 14 of the Sexual Offences Act 1956. He was not charged with having unlawful interc
defaultourse with a girl under 16, contrary to section 6, because a prosecution for that offence had to be brought within 12 months and this one had not 
defaultbeen.
default The four male Law Lords allowed the defendant’s appeal against conviction, on the basis that Parliament
default could have had no possible purpose in prohibiting a prosecution under section 6 after the lapse of 12 months if exactly the same conduct could then be prosecuted under section 14.
default Lord Bingham said that any other result was ‘impossible’ and Lord Steyn th
defaultought the conclusion was ‘inescapable’. Yet Lady Hale, who is so far the only woman to have been appointed to our top court, strongly dissented. For her the only unfairness in the case was that being done by her fellow judges to the young girl and the many
default like her.
default Lady Hale said the Sexual Offences Act was a mess when it was enacted and was an ever greater mess when it was amended. It simply was not possible to discern within it a Parliamentary intention along the lines suggested by her brethren. As she 
defaultput it: ‘Although we do have to try to make sense of the words Parliament has used, we do not have to supply Parliament with the thinking that it never did and the words that it never used.’
default I fervently hope that Lady Hale’s approach to statutory interpre
defaulttation is the one that begins to prevail. As we all know, context is everything.
defaultMy eighth point is that senior judges should begin to exercise the power to overrule precedents for the future only. At present, when they overrule a precedent, one of the par
defaultties to the case at hand bears the consequences of the change to the law, even though that party might have thought the ‘old’ law was perfectly good and had based his or her conduct on it. Prospective overruling avoids this sense of injustice, allowing the
default case at hand to be decided in accordance with the pre-existing law but sending out a message to future litigants that for them the law has changed. The Federal Constitutional Court of Germany has given itself this power, where practical reasons demand it.
default Seven Law Lords asserted it for themselves in the 
defaultSpectrum Plus 
defaultcase last year, but they opted not to make use of it on the facts before them.
default There seems to me to be particular scope for prospective overruling in criminal cases, where it is surely unju
defaultst that a defendant can find him- or herself punished for falling foul of a new interpretation of the law that did not exist at the time the alleged crime was committed.
defaultNinthly, judges should be prepared to consider abstract legal questions, the so-calle
defaultd 
defaultactio popularis
default. They are edging towards doing this, as is evident from cases such as the one taken by 
defaultThe Guardian
default against the statutory ban on campaigning to abolish the monarchy
default or the 
defaultone brought by the Family Planning Association here in Belfast ag
defaultainst the uncertainty inherent in our abortion laws.
default If judges did a lot more of this kind of judging they would help to clarify legal principles and in the process greatly enhance the rule of law. 
default&#xa0;
defaultFinally, and most radically, our top judges should 
defaultclaim for themselves the power to declare Acts of Parliament to be unconstitutional. We should never forget that the doctrine of Parliamentary sovereignty, which supposedly lies at the base of our constitution, is itself a construct of the common law.
default The
default current Attorney General, Lord Goldsmith, expressly stated this in an answer to a Parliamentary question asked by Lord Lester of Herne Hill two years ago.
default Judges can therefore, if so inclined, modify the doctrine. This is what the Law Lords were invited 
defaultto do last year when there was a challenge by the Countryside Alliance to the constitutionality of the Hunting Act 2004, passed by the House of Commons without the consent of the second Chamber.
default While all nine Law Lords held the Act to be valid, because i
defaultt was passed in accordance with the Parliament Act of 1949, which in turn had been passed in accordance with the Parliament Act of 1911, five Law Lords expressly stated
default that if the House of Commons alone were to try to delete from the 1911 Act the section
default which prevents it from extending the maximum permitted life of a Parliament beyond five years, that would 
defaultnot
default be a constitutional Act. Lord Steyn went further, suggesting that courts should be able to invalidate Acts which seek to abolish any fundamental 
defaultfeature of our constitution, such as the right of access to judicial review.
default 
defaultIn 2004, when the government was pushing another of its Asylum and Immigration Bills through Parliament, it inserted a provision
default which would have ousted the jurisdiction of the
default courts to hear challenges against decisions of the immigration appeal tribunals. There was a huge outcry, not least from Lord Woolf, the Lord Chief Justice.
default Eventually the clause was dropped. But if Parliament had gone ahead and enacted it, would courts 
defaulthave held it to be unconstitutional? I very much hope so. Similarly, if in April 2006 the government had not climbed down on its Legislative and Regulatory Reform Bill, under which ministers could have done all sorts of things that only an elected Parliame
defaultnt should be able to do, I like to 
defaultthink that, had a challenge been raised in the courts against a government measure taken under the Act, judges would have declared it too to be unconstitutional. As Gibbon noted in 
defaultThe Decline and Fall of the Roman Empire
default, published around the same time as the American Constitution: ‘The principles of a free constitution are irrecoverably lost, when the legislative power is nominated by the executive’.
default Or, as the US Supreme Court put it in 1966, ‘Where rights secured by t
defaulthe Constitution are involved, there can be no rule making or legislation which would abrogate them’.
default  
