default S. 172(1) of the Constitution of South Africa 1996 (formerly s. 98(5) of the Interim Constitution 1994): ‘When deciding a constitutional matter within its power, a court (a) must declare that any law or conduct that is inconsistent with the Constitution 
defaultis invalid to the extent of its inconsistency; and (b) may make any order that is just and equitable, including (i)
default&#xad;
default an order limiting the retrospective effect of the declaration of invalidity; and (ii) an order suspending the declaration of invalidity for
default any period and on any conditions, to allow the competent authority to correct the defect’. The power to suspend a declaration of invalidity was first exercised in 
defaultS v Ntuli
default 1996 (1) S.A.L.R. 1207, where the government was given some 16 months to produce c
defaultorrective legislation. This deadline was later extended but ultimately the Constitutional Court held that the Minister’s officials had failed to act promptly and diligently and that the order of invalidity must therefore stand: 
defaultMinister of Justice v Ntuli
default 
default(5 June 1997).
